image.altText: A crashed car.

props.synopsis: Several males are on the run after their allegedly stolen car collided with a vehicle and left a man dead in Melbourne's east. Two girls have been arrested.

title.children: Man killed in collision with allegedly stolen car in Melbourne, occupants fled the scene

image.altText: Iris Smit, Inventor of The Quick Flick

props.synopsis: Small beauty entrepreneurs say they are struggling to stop copies of their cosmetics being released because they don't have the legal budgets to fight big companies that are self-confessed dupers.

title.children: 'Is this really ethical?': Iris sees her product being copied weekly, but she can't afford to do anything about it

image.altText: A visualisation of a computer drawing of a face dissolving.

props.synopsis: The privacy of Australian children is being violated on a large scale, with their personal images — and sometimes their names and locations — being used to train the AI powering most of the world's image-generators.

title.children: The world's biggest AI models were trained using images of Australian kids, and their families had no idea

image.altText: A man and woman standing in front of a house

props.synopsis: Investors say they're selling properties in Victoria due to the threat of increased taxes, changing tenancy laws and rising interest rates. But Victoria's not the only state where the number of renters appears to be falling.

title.children: First homebuyers are snapping up rentals as three states show signs of investor sell-off

image.altText: Anthony Albanese looks across the table at Peter Dutton during Question Time.

props.synopsis: This seems as good a time as any to evaluate the reliability of what politicians tell us about the housing crisis — and how they're going to make things better.

title.children: Albanese and Dutton have different approaches to solving the housing crisis. If only either of them could actually work

image.altText: A man holds a sign protesting a TikTok ban with collage cut outs of the US Capitol and TikTok logo

props.synopsis: Brian Firebaugh thanks TikTok for giving him an income, a reality TV victory — and a son. He's one of 170 million American users who could lose access to the app within months.

title.children: This Texas rancher says TikTok's the reason he has a child. Now he's fighting moves to ban the app

image.altText: India Stampede (1)

props.synopsis: A deadly stampede broke out at a religious festival in north India, killing at least 100 people and hospitalising more than 150.

title.children: More than 100 killed during stampede at religious gathering in India

image.altText: Atticus the lost dog with cast on paw

props.synopsis: Atticus the five-year-old staghound was found dumped on a pile of rubbish before being taken to the Lost Dogs' Home in Melbourne. He is just one of many surrendered pets that comes through their door.

title.children: Atticus was left to die on a pile of rubbish. Dog shelters say they are tired of seeing cases like his

image.altText: Kelvin Bellette 2024-05-09

props.synopsis: A Victorian disability pensioner who claims to have been been falsely nominated for nearly 60 traffic infringements says he has had yet another crime wrongly pinned on him.

title.children: Kelvin has almost been cleared of $20,000 in traffic fines, but says false accusations continue

image.altText: Two women walking next to each other on the street. They are wearing face masks and jackets

props.synopsis: COVID-19 continues to evolve at a fast pace, with the latest highly transmissible variant, nicknamed FLuQE emerging as the dominant strain in Australia and across parts of the world.

title.children: Is it FLiRT or FLuQE? What we know about the new dominant COVID variant

image.altText: Rows of cars in a car park, with stacked shipping containers behind them.

props.synopsis: A loophole in the government's New Vehicle Efficiency Standard could be exploited by car makers seeking to import higher-polluting vehicles, and would undermine the first three years of the new climate laws.

title.children: Car import loophole allows manufacturers to rush polluting vehicles into Australia

image.altText: An older man in a suit with a bright red cap gestures as he speaks behind a lectern.

props.synopsis: America's highest court finds ex-presidents have significant protection from criminal prosecution — a historic ruling that's prompted an appeal of Donald Trump's criminal conviction.

title.children: Trump seeks to overturn New York hush money fraud convictions after Supreme Court immunity ruling

image.altText: A young woman in a hijab listens as she sits behind a microphone.

props.synopsis: Suspended Labor MP Fatima Payman has enlisted the advice of a minor party political "whisperer" as her party colleagues brace themselves for the possibility she will move to the crossbench.

title.children: 'She has made a decision': PM unfazed as Fatima Payman enlists 'preference whisperer'

image.altText: A man bing led by police into court.

props.synopsis: Melbourne man Christopher Bell, 53, has been sentenced to seven years' jail after killing George Tereva in a bobcat accident in 2022. Bell had consumed five beers when he took control of the vehicle.

title.children: Victorian man who fatally hit colleague while 'playing chicken' with bobcat jailed

image.altText: A poster with a picture of a young man smiling is partially torn of a wall

props.synopsis: He never finished university. He poses for selfies with screaming fans. His social media gives candid glimpses behind the scenes — and an audience ready to hear him speak.

title.children: Meet the 'lion cub' far-right leader who could soon become France's youngest prime minister

image.altText: A man holding an antique vase

props.synopsis: Starting this month, many Australians travelling to China will no longer need to apply for a visa, but some challenges and inconveniences remain for foreign travellers when it comes to paying in the largely cashless society.

title.children: Australians have visa-free travel to China, but how can they pay in an increasingly cashless society?

image.altText: A man in a suit speaks in front of a crowd.

props.synopsis: UK cities are broke, utility prices are sky high and the cost of living is barely affordable. Sir Keir Starmer is likely to become just the fourth Labour leader to win an election. If he does so, his task is monumental.

title.children: The first Labour leader with a 'Sir' in front of his name may soon be charged with saving the United Kingdom

image.altText: Judy wearing a white sweater, reading a document at her kitchen table.

props.synopsis: A report from a Melbourne law firm calls for reforms to Victoria's rental bond system, arguing too many rental providers are making unreasonable claims on their tenants' bonds.

title.children: Melbourne law firm calls for Victorian landlords who repeatedly make 'baseless' bond claims to be fined

image.altText: A notice in a supermarket that consumers can only purchase two cartons of eggs

props.synopsis: Consumers can expect to pay more for eggs at the check-out in coming weeks as one of Australia's biggest fast-food retail chains limits its breakfast times.

title.children: McDonald's cuts back breakfast hours over egg supply concerns, supermarket prices expected to rise

image.altText: A grey stingray in a tank.

props.synopsis: Reports of Charlotte's pregnancy in February puzzled experts, who questioned how the stingray could have become pregnant having not shared a tank with a male stingray for at least eight years.

title.children: Charlotte, the stingray who reportedly became pregnant without a male ray, dies in US aquarium

image.altText: An AFL umpire holds his hand out towards a Melbourne player who is arguing with him, as other Demons players surround him.

props.synopsis: AFL chief executive Andrew Dillon says despite widespread outcry, the standard of umpiring is as good as ever.

title.children: Umpiring standard as good as ever, says AFL boss

image.altText: A family walking backwards.

props.synopsis: It's the first time in more than 50 years that an infectious disease is among the five leading causes of death in Australia.

title.children: Life expectancy in Australia has fallen for the first time in about 30 years

image.altText: Three Palestinina prisoners holding up their shirts to reveal their stomachs sunken in after prison release.

props.synopsis: Israel has released 54 Palestinian prisoners it held in detention during its war in Gaza, including the director of the enclave's Al-Shifa Hospital, Mohammad Abu Selmeyah.

title.children: Israel releases 54 Palestinians including Al-Shifa Hospital director, who says he was subject to 'psychological and physical torture'

image.altText: A woman with short blonde hair looks off to the side standing in front of a pink cosmetics display.

props.synopsis: Australian cosmetics company MCoBeauty has become a multi-million-dollar business by "duping" popular beauty products. But its success hasn't been without controversy, after pushing the boundaries of the law too far in the past.

title.children: In the makeup world, there's a fine line between duping and being sued. MCoBeauty found out the hard way

image.altText: A man wearing a car backwards stands by a bright green car, with its doors open.

props.synopsis: The man who stole international tennis star Nick Kyrgios's green Tesla from the player's mother at gunpoint is sentenced to four-and-a-half years' jail in the ACT Supreme Court.

title.children: Man who stole Nick Kyrgios's Tesla and held his mother at gunpoint jailed for more than four years

image.altText: The silhouette of a soldier holding a large gun in the window of a home.

props.synopsis: As the war in Ukraine drags into its third year, some Russian soldiers have decided to flee the front lines. This is how they did it.

title.children: 'I ran away, and now they're all dead': The Russian soldiers who escaped the front lines

image.altText: Woman sitting on a park bench.

props.synopsis: Non-fatal strangulation, or choking during sex, is becoming mainstream among young people in Australia — fuelled by pornography and popular culture. It's prompted concerns that those engaging in the practice are not aware of the serious health risks.

title.children: Choking during sex can cause brain injuries but many young Australians are taking up the act

image.altText: An out of focus man and woman walk past a building with glass sliding doors and a sign reading Reserve Bank of Australia.

props.synopsis: Australia's much-discussed narrow path out of the inflation fight is rapidly turning into a highwire act. While one more rate hike from the RBA could cause a recession, holding back if inflation accelerates further will damage its credibility.

title.children: We're richer than everyone else. But one more rate hike could change that

image.altText: a man of african descent stands behind a pool fence

props.synopsis: Tuck was sitting in the pool area of his own apartment complex when police arrested him, believing he was trespassing. He says it wouldn't have happened had it not been for his physical appearance.

title.children: 'Extraordinary overreaction': Man accuses police of racial profiling after arrest for trespassing at his own home

image.altText: Assange and Robinson sit in plane seats, looking happy.

props.synopsis: For the first time, two of the people closest to the negotiations to free Julian Assange have revealed what it took to convince the United States to release the man who had published hundreds of thousands of their most secret documents.

title.children: As Julian Assange languished in a British prison, Anthony Albanese passed a message to his lawyers that would prove a turning point

image.altText: More revelations in the Jeffrey Epstein investigation

props.synopsis: The Florida investigations uncovered Epstein's close ties to former president Bill Clinton and Britain's Prince Andrew, and his once-friendly relationship with former president Donald Trump.

title.children: Newly released transcripts show prosecutors knew of Jeffrey Epstein's underage abuse prior to lenient plea deal

image.altText: Young smiling woman with long dark hair pulled back, holding a baby, whose face is blurred.

props.synopsis: Formerly married couple Robert Samuel Geeves and Anne Margaret Geeves were the last people to see Amber Haigh alive. Twenty-two years after her disappearance, they are facing trial for her alleged murder.

title.children: Amber Haigh's alleged killer used to get her drunk and tie her up before abusing her, witness tells court

image.altText: An unidentified woman stands in front of the Wheel of Brisbane.

props.synopsis: What started as after-work drinks on a Friday evening quickly turned into a nightmare when Jessica* arrived at a popular bar in central Brisbane.

title.children: 'I was completely paralytic': Jessica doesn't know what her drink was spiked with — and that's part of the problem

image.altText: An image of an older lady frowning, she wears a fascinator and looks to be talking to people.

props.synopsis: Princess Anne has expressed her deep regret and says she is saddened to miss the commemoration event in Canada as she recovers from recent injuries.

title.children: Princess Anne expresses 'deep regret' at missing World War I commemoration in Canada

image.altText: Barry Foreman leans on a box inside a Fedex warehouse

props.synopsis: More people are retiring later in life. Here's how these Australians stay happy and engaged at work.

title.children: This 77-year-old is thriving alongside his Gen Z colleagues. Here's his secret to career longevity
